We need to compute $\int_{0}^{\pi} \sin x \cdot f(\cos x) \, dx$ using the substitution $y = \cos x$.

When $x = 0$, $y = \cos 0 = 1$.

When $x = \pi$, $y = \cos \pi = -1$.

The derivative $dy/dx = -\sin x$, so $dx = -dy / \sin x$.

The integral becomes $\int_{1}^{-1} \sin x \cdot f(y) \cdot \left(-\frac{1}{\sin x}\right) \, dy$.

This simplifies to $\int_{-1}^{1} f(y) \, dy$.

So we need to show that $\int_{0}^{\pi} \sin x \cdot f(\cos x) \, dx = \int_{-1}^{1} f(y) \, dy$.

In Lean, we can use the `intervalIntegral.integral_comp_subst` lemma to perform the change of variables.

```tactics
