```

To prove this, we'll use the change of variables formula. The formula is:

$\int_{a}^{b} f(x) \cdot g'(x) \, dx = \int_{g(a)}^{g(b)} f(g(x)) \, dg(x)$

In our case, we have $\int_{0}^{\pi} \sin x \cdot f(\cos x) \, dx$. Here, $f(x) = \sin x$ and $g(x) = \cos x$. Then $g'(x) = -\sin x$.

The change of variables gives us:

