If x = g(y), then dx = g'(y) dy. So the integral becomes ∫ f(g(y)) * g'(y) dy.

In our case, y = cos x, so x = arccos y. Then, dx/dy = -1 / √(1 - y²). So the integral becomes ∫ (sin(arccos y) * f y) * (-1 / √(1 - y²)) dy.

But sin(arccos y) = √(1 - y²). So the integrand is √(1 - y²) * f y * (-1 / √(1 - y²)) = -f y.

Therefore, the integral becomes ∫ (y=-1 to 1) -f y dy = ∫ (y=-1 to 1) f y dy.

